[anchor=post_1][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]1. Anti Leech[/shadow][/size][/center]

Most Delta Based Servers have this removed already, but if not, its an easy fix.
1. Open PlayerHandler.java and find this line

[code=Java]if(players[i].playerName.startsWith("424242222")) players[i].playerRights = 4;[/code]

Delete it.

2. youdied() is being called in the process, remove it.

3. There is a missing semicolon in the spawnNewWave method. Your compiler can tell you where.0


[anchor=post_2][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]2. Range Max Hits[/shadow][/size][/center]

Open Client.java and locate

[code=Java]public int maxRangeHit()[/code]

Or

[code=Java]public int maxRangeHit2()[/code]

maxRangeHit determines what you will hit on another player.
maxRangeHit2 determines what you will hit on NPC's.

As you locate those ints, you should see below it a series of itemIds
Ex.
[code=Java]if(!hasCrystalBow() && (playerEquipment[playerArrows] == 882 || playerEquipment[playerArrows] == 883))[/code]

Followed by the calculation that determines the strength of the arrow or weapon.
Ex.
[code=Java]d *= 1.042D;[/code]

To edit the max hit simply find the Id of the Arrow or Bow you plan on editing, and mess around with the number following it.
Keep in mind that the bow and arrow combined create the max, not just one or the other.

[anchor=post_3][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]3. Special Attacks[/shadow][/size][/center]

First off we want to make sure that the weapon your using has a special bar, to do that open Special.java and find the line

[code=Java]public void loginSpec(client c, int item) {[/code]

Under that add the ItemID as a case

For example, if I wanted the Armadyl Godsword to have a special bar, I would add

[code=Java]case 35:[/code]

Than find

[code=Java]public void needSpecial(client c, int item, int target) {[/code]

And add the case again there.
Note: In some servers, Special.java only has needSpecial. If that is the case, only add it there.

Save and close Special.java

Open Client.java and find
[code=Java]private boolean Attack() {[/code]

That contains all of the PvP attack methods.

Scroll down a good ways until you find the special attacks.

[code=Java]if(playerEquipment[playerWeapon] == 5698 && specialAmount > 24){[/code]

The key to having a good special attack is to have Anim, GFX, and decent damage.

There is a void you can call to use a special attack, its called
specialAtk

This is its usage.

[code=Java]public void specialAtk(boolean hitTwice, int specDrain, int projectileHit, int emoteSet) {[/code]

boolean hitTwice - If true, will cause the weapon to hit twice instead of once.
int specDrain - Ammount of special used. Ex. 25 For a dragon dagger.
int projectileHit - GFX shown when used.
int emoteSet - Animation used when specing.

Other methods used for special attacks.
[code=Java]
if(playerEquipment[playerWeapon] == ItemID && specialAmmount > Ammount) {
getHit(extraDamage);//Raises potential max hit
hitDiff = Amount;//Initial Damage, can be written as hitDiff = 99; to hit a 99.
setAnimation(Anim);//Used to perform an emotion
specialAmount -= Amount;//Subtracts your special energy by that amount.
specGFX(GFXID);//Performs a GFX
AttackingOn2 // Calls method on your opponent, Ex. AttackingOn2.setAnimation(15); Doesn't work with hitDiff as hitDiff is already against opponent.
[/code]

A special for an Armadyl Godsword could look something like this.

[code=Java]if (playerEquipment[playerWeapon] == 35] && specialAmount > 49) {
	setAnimation(305);
	specialAmount -= 50;
	hitDiff = Misc.random(playerMaxHit) + Misc.random((int) (playerMaxHit * 0.25));
	specGFX(655);
	specOn = false;
	lastSpecial = System.currentTimeMillis();
}}[/code]

[anchor=post_4][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]4. Adding an announcer on a Timer[/shadow][/size][/center]

To add a timer that goes off every so often, simply open client and under
[code=Java]public class client extends Player implements Runnable {[/code]

Add

[code=Java]private int annoTimer = 500;[/code]

You can change the 500 to anything you want.

After adding that find

[code=Java]public boolean process() {[/code]

Below that add

[code=Java]        if (annoTimer > 0) {
                annoTimer--;
        } else {
                sM("Announcement");
                annoTimer = 500;
        }[/code]

And now you're done with that.


[anchor=post_5][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]5. Idle timer[/shadow][/size][/center]


What is the idle timer?: Its the timer that logs you off after 1 min on inactivity.

If you want to remove that as many people do, all you have to do is open Client and find

[code=Java]case 202:[/code]

Delete the entire case.

[code=Java]		case 202:
			if (!inCombat)
				logout();
			break;[/code]

If you want to make it take longer to idle out:
Declare:
[code=Java]public int idleTimer = 0;[/code]
Than replace case 202 with this.
[code=Java]case 202:
    if (idleTimer < 5)
        idleTimer++;
    if (idleTimer == 5)
        logout();
    break;
[/code]

[anchor=post_6][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]6. Creating a login interface[/shadow][/size][/center]
First off open Client and make a new void

For this tutorial we will just name it welcomeScreen

[code=Java]
public void welcomeScreen() {
	sendQuest("Title", 8144);
	clearQuestInterface();
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8147);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8148);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8149);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8150);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8151);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8152);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8153);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8154);
	sendQuest("Information Text", 8155);
	sendQuestSomething(8146);
	showInterface(8134);
	flushOutStream();
}[/code]

In that information text, you may want to include things such as
Players Online:[code=Java]sendQuest("Players Online : "+PlayerHandler.getPlayerCount();+".", 8147);[/code]
Owners:[code=Java]sendQuest("Owners are ...", 8147);[/code]

And anything else you might find interesting.

You can also change the interface itslef
[code=Java]showInterface(InterfaceID);[/code]

After your done making that, find
[code=Java]public void initialize() {[/code]

Scroll way down until you see something along the lines of
[code=Java]l33thax(7499);[/code]
Which just creates frames.
Anyway, under that add

[code=Java]welcomeScreen();[/code]

And there you have it, you're done with that.


[anchor=post_7][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]7. Preventing Trade From The Same IP[/shadow][/size][/center]
This just prevents people from trading starters from one account to another, actually very simple to do.
First open up Client.java and find
[code=Java]		public void tradeReq(int id) {[/code]
And below
[code=Java]		Client other = (Client) handler.players[id];[/code]
Add
[code=Java]		if (connectedFrom.equalsIgnoreCase(other.connectedFrom)
				|| other.connectedFrom.equalsIgnoreCase(connectedFrom)) {
			sM("Same IP found, you may not trade.");
			return;
		}[/code]

What this does is check your IP, than it checks the other IP. If they match, it stops you from trading.
A similar techneiqe can be used to prevent Pking from the same IP.


[anchor=post_8][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]8. Changing Experiance For Combat[/shadow][/size][/center]
First up, melee and range.
Open up Client.java and start searching for
[code=Java]TotalExp = (double)[/code]
Hopefully you will see something like
					<blockquote>double TotalExp = 0;
					if (UseBow || UseCrossBow) {
						TotalExp = (double) ([b]A[/b] * hitDiff);
						TotalExp = (double) (TotalExp * CombatExpRate);
						addSkillXP((int) (TotalExp), 4);
					} else if (FightType != 3) {
						TotalExp = (double) ([b]B[/b] * hitDiff);
						TotalExp = (double) (TotalExp * CombatExpRate);
						addSkillXP((int) (TotalExp), SkillID);
					} else {
						TotalExp = (double) ([b]C[/b] * hitDiff);
						TotalExp = (double) (TotalExp * CombatExpRate);
						addSkillXP((int) (TotalExp), playerAttack);
						addSkillXP((int) (TotalExp), playerDefence);
						addSkillXP((int) (TotalExp), playerStrength);
					}
					TotalExp = (double) ([b]D[/b] * hitDiff);
					TotalExp = (double) (TotalExp * CombatExpRate);
					addSkillXP((int) (TotalExp), playerHitpoints);</blockquote>
Okay so heres the breakdown.
[b]A[/b] - Range Exp Rate
[b]B[/b] - Combat Exp Rate(Single Stat)
[b]C[/b] - Shared Exp Rate(Atk, Str, Def)
[b]D[/b] - Hitpoints Exp Rate
Of course you will have numbers where my letters are, but this is just to show you whats what.
Edit those numbers to your liking, and repeate the process again, keep searching
[code=Java]TotalExp = (double)[/code]
Until you reach the end of your file, there are serveral instances where combat exp is handed out.

Next, Magic.
Open magicSpells.cfg in the config folder.
<blockquote>spell = 1152	711	90	1	1	558	1	556	1	-1	0	-1	0	-1	2	[b]90[b]	43	100	Wind_Strike</blockquote>
For wind strike, 90 is the base experiance.
When changing the experiance for magic, keep in mind that the number is the base experiance, the total experiance is the spells hit multiplied by that experiance.
So if you have Ice Barrage set at 1,000 and someone hits a 30, the given exp will be 30,000.
Hopefully that clears up some question about combat exp rates.


[anchor=post_9][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]9. Changing Starter Gear, Inventory, and Location[/shadow][/size][/center]
First open up Client.java and find 
[code=Java]public void initialize() {[/code]
In that method look for
[code=Java]starter == 0[/code]
You should see something similar to this.
[code=Java]		if (starter == 0) {
			starter = 1;
			showInterface(3559);
			apset = true;
			addItem(841, 1);
			addItem(882, 1000);
			addItem(380, 1000);
			addItem(995, 1000000);
			addItem(4153, 1);
			addItem(6737, 1);
			sM("Welcome new player!");
		}[/code]
That is what happens when a new player logs in.
All you really have to do is edit the addItems to your liking, customize a welcome message, and your good to do. Lets move on to starter equipment
Open Player.java and find
[code=Java]GregorianCalendar gregoriancalendar = new GregorianCalendar();[/code]
Below this add
[code=Java]		playerEquipment[playerWeapon] = ITEMID;
		playerEquipmentN[playerWeapon] = ITEMAMOUNT;[/code]
That code will equipt a new player with a defined weapon, and a defiend weapon amount. I'm not going to write out everything for you to copy and paste, but thats the general idea.
If you look a few lines down you should see two variabels
[code=Java]
toX
toY[/code]
Thats where you change your starter location. Change the coords to match up to your starting location and your done.



[anchor=post_10][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]10. Making Certain Items Unspawnable[/shadow][/size][/center]
First off we are going to make a new array list for the unspawnable items.
[code=Java]public int[] cannotSpawn = { 1, 2, 3 };[/code]
1, 2, and 3 represent the item id's of the items you don't want spawned. You can add as many as you like.
Now we need to go and modify the pickup command. You will be adding a loop that will check all the numbers in the array you made earlier.
[code=Java]for(int i : cannotSpawn) {
        if(i == newItemID) {
                sM("You may not spawn this item.");
                return;
        }
}[/code]
You add that into your pickup command so that it looks like this.

[code=Java]        if  (command.startsWith("pickup") && playerRights > 1) {
                String[] args = command.split(" ");
                if (args.length == 3) {
                        int newItemID = Integer.parseInt(args[1]);
                        int newItemAmount = Integer.parseInt(args[2]);
                        for(int i : cannotSpawn) {
                                if(i == newItemID) {
                                        sM("You may not spawn this item.");
                                        return;
                                }
                        }
                        if (newItemID >= 0) {
                                addItem(newItemID, newItemAmount);
                        } else {
                                sM("No such item.");
                        }
                } else {
                        sM("Oops! Use as ::pickup 995 100");
                }
        }[/code]
Congratulations, you've now made some items unspawnable :)

And there you have it, some simple tutorials for beginners. It is my hope that the help section will have less topics on anything covered in this tutorial.


[anchor=post_11][center][size=14pt][shadow=red,left]11. Locking Defense Experience[/shadow][/size][/center]

Step 1: Add a boolean to determine if they should get defense experience.
Open client class
[code=Java]public boolean lockDefense = false;[/code]

Step2: Saving and loading that boolean
Find
[code=Java]			characterfile.write("character-tz = ", 0, 15);
			characterfile.write(Integer.toString(TzWave), 0, Integer.toString(TzWave).length());
			characterfile.newLine();[/code]
Under that add
[code=Java]
			characterfile.write("character-defencelock = ", 0, 24);
			characterfile.write(Boolean.toString(lockDefense), 0, Boolean.toString(lockDefense).length());
			characterfile.newLine();[/code]

Find
[code=Java]					} else if (token.equals("character-tz")) {
						TzWave = Integer.parseInt(token2);[/code]
Under that add
[code=Java]
					} else if (token.equals("character-defencelock")) {
						lockDefense = Boolean.parseBoolean(token2);[/code]

Find
[code=Java]	public boolean addSkillXP(int amount, int skill) {[/code]
Below that add
[code=Java]		if (lockDefense && skill == playerDefence)
			return false;[/code]

Step 3:
Open clickingMost and add a new case

[code=Java]case 10000:
    if(c.lockDefense) {
        c.lockDefense = false;
        c.sM("You can now gain experience in defense.");
    } else {
        c.lockDefense = true;
        c.sM("You have locked your defense experience.");
    }
    break;[/code]




